Spring on my mind ✨

🌈 AI generated “Kuna Mola Textile + Mexican Huipile” 🤯  Inspiration for a new genre of everything - if cultural IP is tied back to original source it could open up revenue generation opportunities and creative collaboration on another level ✨ how are we feeling about a future with the robots? 🤖

On a personal note…it’s Earth week so no better time than to share an org I’ve been volunteering with over the past few months. @onamission.world is a Swiss non-profit on a mission (pun intended) to restore forests and empower communities. 

Madagascar (photo) is a country where 90% of the native forests have been destroyed. The island is super rich in culture and diversity and these reforestation projects help support people, land, and animals in significant ways. This project is in scaling phase with 1.4 M mangrove trees planted each month.

We in the artisan sector are on a mission to preserve craft and provide fair paying jobs to craftsmen and women around the globe. Although less emission causing as standard production there are still negative externalities that result in the making and shipping of goods.

Want to get clear on your carbon emissions? Where you can reduce? And then offset the rest by supporting reforestation projects? We can help calculate (for free) and work with you to make a plan. It’s going to take all of us looking in the mirror and making bold decisions for the sake of our planet and it’s people. Link in bio or DM me! ~ Harper
Working on something new/fun with my friend @freexbrave 💜👀

It started with a necklace and a desire to create an alternative to the artisan to manufacturer pipeline. How to leverage  the creativity and cultural knowledge of traditional craft and folk artists to build new revenue streams? We (jk it’s just me, Harper) are launching our first new product in over 5 years. L’Oiseau is a fine art print inspired by a hammered metal bird necklace from Mali. 10% of full sales price of each print will go back to artists as a royalty payment. Printed on yummy 100% cotton rag paper and deigned by @freexbrave 🤙 link in bio ✨print in stories ☀️

Today is World Ocean’s Day. What a privilege it is to be able to spend time in the water, away from our phones, adapting to the literal ebs and flows minute by minute, connecting to something much bigger than each of us. I can’t imagine anything more important than protecting that life force. 🌊✨❤️ #worldoceansday

L’Oiseau, our first (of many) art prints launched this week 🐦 excited to partner with more and more folk artists from around the globe to compensate them for their creativity, cultural knowledge—that initial spark ✨ $12 or 10% of each 20 x 30 print (shown here) goes back to artist as a royalty payment for inspiring the collection, as a collaborator in the creative process ❤️
It is possible to design for optimal outcomes ✨ just takes a different kind of effort ❤️

If you know me you know how much I love Mali…the music, the textiles, the people ❤️Felt right to choose Malian artists to benefit from our first print. Mali Chic is a gallery in the hippodrome neighborhood of Bamako. I spent a month with them years ago visiting artisans in and around Bamako and Segou. Since then they have visited often in the US and I try and support them and the artists they represent as much as I can. These yummy 100% cotton rag prints are a new experiment in compensating for creativity. Malian playlist coming up soon 🎶🎸
I’ve been obsessed with these vibrant, dense floral embroideries from Huixtan, Chiapas. Might they inspire our next prints? 🌺🌸❤️
Collab we did with @shoptilonia is back in stock in their shop 💙 Inspired by mud cloth patterns, hand printed in India 💙✨
Eid Mubarak 🌙 @visualsbyponzio via @mali_paw_b_di

Inspiration? Sure. But it’s so much more…it’s that spark that kicks off the creative process, that builds a collection. We want to provide opportunities for global folk artists to build revenue as designers, creative directors, and artists. Passive income could unlock financial freedom that is hard to achieve in trad supply chains and without the negative externalities on the planet. Our first print compensates the jewelry artist from Mali who made this piece here 🦜✨
Musée National Boubou-Hama in Niamey, Niger 💙🤍 photo Joe penny
Scenes from Mopti ✨ origin of L’Oiseau, bird motif featured in our first print 📷 @carlets58 via @mali_paw_b_di

We are NOT here to grow at any and all costs. We are here to be as thoughtful as possible to maximize impact through our prints. 2️⃣8️⃣…royalties from the sale of 28 L’Oiseau prints provide a monthly living wage for artist in Mali and only creates equivalent of $.06 kg/CO2. Net 👏Positive 👏Impact👏 for 🧍‍♀️🧍‍♂️🌏 Link in bio to see our first print and NEW designs coming soon!

Indigenous peoples have protected their forests, marsh lands, and coasts for generations and generations. It would be wise to let them lead as we work to reforest, protect biodiversity, and reconnect with nature so our planet can heal. #indigenouspeoplesday #worldindigenouspeoplesday

New prints up! Made in collaboration with @leste_br “Huixtan” and “Chiapas Flora” prints were inspired by brightly colored, densely embroidered florals from Huixtan, a town in the Southern Mexican State of Chiapas 🌺🌸 Embroidery artists in Huixtan will receive royalties for sale of each print creating passive income oppprtunities and a novel way to highlight the ART in ARTisan ✨ thanks @kiptik for your partnership as always 💗

Our new prints ‘Chiapas Flora’ and ‘Huixtan’ were inspired by the embroidery work of ‘Las Dalias’ a group of artists working in Huixtan, Chiapas 🌺 

The artists will receive royalties for each print sold for inspiring the designs. 43 prints sold per month will equal a living wage salary to support a standard family in this region of Mexico. Passive income 🤝Fine Art ✨ #moreimpactlessstuff

Ubuntu is a Xhosa word originating from a South African philosophy that centers on how to live a life well, together. Ubuntu asks for you to consider if your actions also benefit that of the collective. I Am Because We Are: your life IS your relationship to others.
‘Chiapas Flora’ 💚 12% of the sale of each print goes back to the artists in Chiapas, Mexico whose embroidered florals inspired the print 🌺 link in bio ✨

There are 8 recognized indigenous tribes in NC (where I live). Those of us working in the craft sector often travel to far away places to work with indigenous peoples, learning about their culture and craft. It’s important to remember that our land here in the US was tended to for thousands and thousands of years by tribes native to these lands. They intimately knew/know the hills, forests, and waters and raised their families to carry this knowledge forward. The dress shown here is from the Lumbee tribe. I’d love to learn more about the indigenous customs from the land I am currently living on. ❤️#indigenouspeoplesday

Why prints? Why royalties? For the most part artisans generate income by producing physical products for brands or selling direct to end customer (less common). With this model, their livelihoods are directly connected to their ability to produce. And the more they can produce, the more income they receive. Make more, sell more, ship more, rinse and repeat. The thing with this model is that the countries with the most infrastructure, resources, and competitive labor costs always get the most opportunities. Countries/regions without developed supply chains are not without creativity or cultural knowledge though, so developing a market to compensate for these skills seems super important. Prints provide an avenue to showcase designs and motifs in an elevated way with royalties attributing back to the artist(s) whose work inspired the print design. Passive income for creativity and cultural knowledge ❤️ #moreimpactlessstuff #lessstuffmoreimpact

Now through Dec 8, we’re doubling royalties to 24% for each print sold. That’s $23 (avg…depends on print size) in passive income, compensating global artists for their  cultural knowledge and individual creativity. In Mali that equates to a month living wage salary with sale a single print 💛
